aa(lp246
VI'll use one last example here.
p247
aVOne poll found that 41 percent of Muslims in this country support jihad,
p248
aVwhich is obviously pretty scary,
p249
aVand it was reported everywhere in 2015.
p250
aVWhen I want to check a number like that,
p251
aVI'll start off by finding the original questionnaire.
p252
aVIt turns out that journalists who reported on that statistic
p253
aVignored a question lower down on the survey
p254
aVthat asked respondents how they defined "jihad."
p255
aVAnd most of them defined it as,
p256
aV"Muslims' personal, peaceful struggle to be more religious."
p257
aVOnly 16 percent defined it as, "violent holy war against unbelievers."
p258
aVThis is the really important point:
p259
aVbased on those numbers, it's totally possible
p260
aVthat no one in the survey who defined it as violent holy war
p261
aValso said they support it.
p262
aVThose two groups might not overlap at all.
p263
aa(lp264
VIt's also worth asking how the survey was carried out.
p265
aVThis was something called an opt-in poll,
p266
aVwhich means anyone could have found it on the internet and completed it.
p267
aVThere's no way of knowing if those people even identified as Muslim.
p268
aVAnd finally, there were 600 respondents in that poll.
p269
aVThere are roughly three million Muslims in this country,
p270
aVaccording to Pew Research Center.
p271
aVThat means the poll spoke to roughly one in every 5,000 Muslims
p272
aVin this country.
p273
aa(lp274
VThis is one of the reasons
p275
aVwhy government statistics are often better than private statistics.
p276
aVA poll might speak to a couple hundred people, maybe a thousand,
p277
aVor if you're L'Oreal, trying to sell skin care products in 2005,
p278
aVthen you spoke to 48 women to claim that they work.
p279
aa(lp280
V(Laughter)
